00:07:07.060 --> 00:07:08.130
they know to check for pregnancy,

00:07:08.130 --> 00:07:10.050
because they start feeling the legs,

00:07:10.050 --> 00:07:11.320
the legs start bothering them.

00:07:11.320 --> 00:07:12.540
That's restless legs.

00:07:12.540 --> 00:07:14.520
Delayed sleep phase syndrome,

00:07:14.520 --> 00:07:16.090
second most common sleep disorder

00:07:16.090 --> 00:07:19.930
among young adults and
teenagers, the most common simply

00:07:19.930 --> 00:07:22.700
being behaviorally induced
insufficient sleep syndrome.

00:07:22.700 --> 00:07:24.540
People who just don't get enough sleep

00:07:24.540 --> 00:07:26.150
for their own reasons.

00:07:26.150 --> 00:07:27.730
Which is very weird, by the way.

00:07:27.730 --> 00:07:28.820
Animals don't do that.

00:07:28.820 --> 00:07:31.690
Animals don't just stay awake
for the fun of it usually.

00:07:31.690 --> 00:07:33.430
Usually they sleep on a rhythm.

00:07:33.430 --> 00:07:36.330
But delayed sleep phase syndrome,

00:07:36.330 --> 00:07:38.610
characterized by difficulty falling asleep

00:07:38.610 --> 00:07:40.540
rather than staying asleep.

00:07:40.540 --> 00:07:41.890
If you've never made a diagnosis,

00:07:41.890 --> 00:07:42.893
it's because you've missed it.

00:07:42.893 --> 00:07:44.770
It's just that common.

00:07:44.770 --> 00:07:47.570
Look it up, learn it, you're
gonna start seeing it.

00:07:47.570 --> 00:07:48.550
Delayed sleep phase syndrome,

00:07:48.550 --> 00:07:50.660
characterized by
difficulty falling asleep,

00:07:50.660 --> 00:07:52.250
not staying asleep.

00:07:52.250 --> 00:07:54.530
Most of the time you talk
with an adult with insomnia

00:07:54.530 --> 00:07:56.027
or sleep problems, they say things like,

00:07:56.027 --> 00:07:56.893
"Doc, I have no trouble falling asleep,

00:07:56.893 --> 00:07:59.300
"I have trouble staying asleep."

00:07:59.300 --> 00:08:00.133
This is the opposite.

00:08:00.133 --> 00:08:01.177
"I have trouble falling asleep,

00:08:01.177 --> 00:08:03.790
"but once I fall asleep, I'm just fine."

00:08:03.790 --> 00:08:05.250
Interestingly, delayed
sleep phase syndrome

00:08:05.250 --> 00:08:06.890
was first described in 1981,

00:08:06.890 --> 00:08:09.350
at Montefiore Hospital, New York City,

00:08:09.350 --> 00:08:12.860
where I trained a few years later.

00:08:12.860 --> 00:08:14.730
And it was described among
a group of young adults

00:08:14.730 --> 00:08:17.830
who had what was called at
that point atypical depression.

00:08:17.830 --> 00:08:19.607
What was atypical about
their depression was

00:08:19.607 --> 00:08:21.720
the insomnia pattern was different.

00:08:21.720 --> 00:08:23.570
They had trouble falling
asleep, not staying asleep,

00:08:23.570 --> 00:08:26.060
and didn't have the other
feature sometimes of depression

00:08:26.060 --> 00:08:28.070
called terminal insomnia,
which is a bad term,

00:08:28.070 --> 00:08:31.570
terminal insomnia, which means insomnia

00:08:31.570 --> 00:08:33.060
at the early morning hours.

00:08:33.060 --> 00:08:35.036
But the other thing
about these individuals,

00:08:35.036 --> 00:08:37.230
these young individuals,

00:08:37.230 --> 00:08:40.550
was that they did not
respond to medication.

00:08:40.550 --> 00:08:41.610
None of the antidepressants at the time

00:08:41.610 --> 00:08:43.290
seemed to make any difference to them.

00:08:43.290 --> 00:08:45.760
Once it was identified as
a circadian sleep disorder,

00:08:45.760 --> 00:08:47.894
and it was the first circadian
sleep disorder identified,

00:08:47.894 --> 00:08:49.950
they reset their sleep schedules,

00:08:49.950 --> 00:08:52.810
and once that happened,
their sleep normalized,

00:08:52.810 --> 00:08:55.415
and they felt better
and their mood improved.

